The name Wawne comes from the Anglo_Saxon{Wawi}or{Waghen}which means {'stinking bog',}a reminder of how close it lies to the River Hull with its flat valley.
The only local higher ground is a gravel ridge layed down during the last Ice_Age. A road connecting Wawne with its 'daughter' settlement of {Sudtone (now Sutton)}runs along the top of the ridge, passing between the open fields of Medieval Sutton and South to the old villages that now make up part of{East Hull.}
Modern day Bransholme sprawls either side of this road and stretches almost to the river in places.
